<div class="grid">
  <div class="grid__item three-fifths lap-one-half palm-one-whole">
    <p class="lead">Struggling to use FreeBMD? Not finding someone you expected to find?  Not sure what to do next?  This page contains answers to common problems, and has links to more detailed information.</p>
    <p>Civil (Government) Registration of births, marriages and deaths in England and Wales has been a legal obligation since 1837.  The government department responsible is the General Register Office (the GRO). The GRO is responsible for preparing an index of the registrations, and FreeBMD is a charity project to provide free access to that index.</p>
    <p>As a minimum, the index gives the information that will help you identify the person you are looking for — or at least a small group of people which might include the person you are looking for. You will need this information, to order a certified copy of the register entry (commonly known as a certificate) from the GRO. The certificate contains a lot more information than the index.</p>
    <p>For example, this is the information in a FreeBMD search result:</p>
    <figure class="site site--wide" style="max-width: 707px;">
      <%= image_tag 'entry-information.png?sha=f8c97e7e64a5bc25', alt: 'Entry Information', width: 574, height: 360 %>
      <figcaption>The information available in the index for a death registered in 1907</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>And this is the certificate:</p>
    <figure class="site site--wide">
      <%= image_tag 'death-cert.png?sha=6da809cc966ee522', alt: 'Death certificate', width: 1122, height: 341 %>
      <figcaption>Part of the death certificate with all the details</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <hr class="rule" />
  </div>
